items.body:
Add support for the three new client_options `quota_project_id`, `scopes`, and `credentials_file`.  These options are implemented on the mirogenerator, so the completion of the migration may automatically fulfill this.

https://googleapis.dev/python/google-api-core/latest/client_options.html

items.title: Docs: remove Python 2.7 support and change descriptions on virtual environment

labels.name: api: logging
labels.description: Issues related to the Stackdriver Logging API.

labels.name: triage me
labels.description: I really want to be triaged.

items.body:
#### Environment details

  - OS type and version: any
  - Python version: any
  - pip version: any
  - `google-cloud-logging` version: any

#### Steps to reproduce

  1. Read [Installation](https://github.com/googleapis/python-logging#installation) section of `README.rst`
  2. Find the step to install `virtualenv`

#### Code example

Given Python 2.7 support is removed in January 1, 2020 and the oldest supported version is Python 3.5, we can expect that all environments are with `venv` that is included in the standard modules and is alternative of `virtualenv` in this use case. So we can replace the installation documents with the following descriptions:

* macOS/Linux

```
python -m venv <your-env>
source <your-env>/bin/activate
<your-env>/bin/pip install google-cloud-logging
```

* Windows

```
python -m venv <your-env>
<your-env>\Scripts\activate
<your-env>\Scripts\pip.exe install google-cloud-logging
```

#### Stack trace

N/A

items.title: Enable retries on RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED

labels.name: api: logging
labels.description: Issues related to the Stackdriver Logging API.

labels.name: type: question
labels.description: Request for information or clarification. Not an issue.

items.body:
Hi,

In project I'm working on we started to face **Log ingestion requests per minute** issue. In this case, python throws exception with **RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED** error status code, which also means that this log message is lost for Stackdriver.

As I saw from source code (pls correct me if I'm wrong), there's some kind of retry mechanism implemented during writing logs, but only for certain error codes. So it would be great to have ability to customize retries when write logs to Stackdriver (I my case I want to enable retry on **RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED** error)

Thanks in advance.

Attaching link to question on Stackoverflow: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/60799003/configure-stackdriver-logging-to-retry-on-resource-exhausted

items.title: Create a google-cloud-audit virtual package

labels.name: api: logging
labels.description: Issues related to the Stackdriver Logging API.

labels.name: type: feature request
labels.description: ‘Nice-to-have’ improvement, new feature or different behavior or design.

items.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
Yes, users of the logging module are [opening spurious bugs](https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-python/issues/5322) and [conflating issues](https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-python/issues/3218) due to the lack of a clear path to deserializing AuditLog objects

Without the presence of a python compiled copy of [the AuditLog protocol definition](https://github.com/googleapis/googleapis/blob/master/google/cloud/audit/audit_log.proto), users of the logging client library cannot deserialize [audit log entries](https://cloud.google.com/logging/docs/audit/understanding-audit-logs) that have been returned by the logging API in the form of a serialized `proto_payload`.

Last summer @tseaver [rightly points out](https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-python/issues/5514#issuecomment-399200147) that it cannot be expected for the logging module to assume the type of a field declared as `Any`. However given that the [LogEntry protocol definition](https://github.com/jmorenog/googleapis-googleapis/blob/2b09d506fa548359bec747ef7757e43dd58e348f/google/api/servicecontrol/v1/log_entry.proto#L54-L57) suggests that AuditLog is the _only_ currently accepted type it seems a poor developer experience for users to need to understand protobuf well enough to download and compile the definition themselves.

 **Describe the solution you'd like**
The creation of a new `google-cloud-audit` virtual package containing the python version of the AuditLog protocol definition.

 **Describe alternatives you've considered**
As a workaround I have followed [this users link to stackoverflow](https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-python/issues/5313#issuecomment-399237060) and compiled the AuditLog pb definition into my project manually.
